    <p class="lead">Three representative service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of what we see on Speed Queen service.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Speed Queen AWN432SP top-load washer, Pasadena</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Owner noticed water under the unit during the spin cycle. Small puddle, growing over a week of normal use. Some oily residue visible in the puddle. No fault code displayed (mechanical-control variant). Unit was 9 years old, bought in 2016 for a Bungalow Heaven Pasadena laundry room.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Classic 2015-2020 TR-series transmission seal failure pattern. Year 9, right in the planned-service window. Oily residue confirmed gear oil from transmission. Tub seal and basket drive tested separately, both within spec. Pump and inlet valve clean.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Transmission seal replacement with OEM Speed Queen part. Drained transmission, replaced seal, refilled with correct gear oil grade, reassembled, ran 3 test spin cycles to verify no leak. Owner appreciated being told the unit was on its planned service schedule, not failing.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $485 total. Same-day, 2.5 hours on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Speed Queen ADG3SRGS173TW01 gas dryer, San Marino</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Dryer running but not heating. Clothes coming out damp at end of cycle. Owner had cleaned the lint trap. Unit was 11 years old, gas service to a dedicated laundry room.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Tested gas valve coil amp draw: open circuit. Year 11 gas valve coil failure — within standard ADG-series service window. Igniter and flame sensor tested clean (would have been replacement candidates if they had failed first, common pairing). Drum belt and idler pulley inspected and within spec.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Gas valve coil replacement with OEM Speed Queen part (in stock on truck — common ADG-series item). Verified ignition sequence, full heat cycle, and proper combustion. CSLB C-20 licensed gas work.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $325 total. Same-day, 90 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Speed Queen AFN50RSP front-load washer, Glendale</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Washer wouldn't start when door was closed. Lights came on, panel responsive, but pressing START produced no response. Owner had unplugged and replugged the unit. Issue persisted. Unit was 7 years old in a remodeled Glendale Adams Hill laundry room.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Tested door latch / interlock circuit. Latch mechanism engaging but the interlock signal not registering at the control board. Year 7 latch wear, microswitch fatigue from heavy cycle counts (owner ran the washer 6-7 days per week — typical Speed Queen owner profile). Drum bearing, pump, and door boot all tested within spec.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Door latch / interlock assembly replacement with OEM Speed Queen part. Verified start sequence and full wash cycle. Confirmed normal door-closed signal at control board.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $325 total. Same-day, 90 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
